<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-180-398  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 180 398.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  April 11 1989 v3 n15 p1(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT MacWEEK Inc. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Apple plans networking product blitz for June; token-ring links,AppleTalk upgrade set. (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Swartz, Jon.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Apple Computer plans to make several announcements on June 7th,1989 pertaining to its latest efforts in connectivity.andP;  Apple willintroduce the $1,200 TokenTalk adapter card it co-developed withSytek Inc which connects Macintoshes up to a 4M-bps IBM Token-Ringnetwork.andP;  Apple is working on a 16M-bps card for release in 1990.andO;Version 2.0 of the AppleTalk network management software is setfor release on July 7th.andP;  The new version will increase the nodelimit on AppleTalk networks from 255 nodes to a theoretical 65,025and will add built-in connections to Ethernet and token-ringnetworks.andP;  The firm is also introducing the AppleTalk InternetRouter software which will supply connections to Ethernet andtoken-ring local area networks and will connect up to eightAppleTalk networks.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Apple Computer Inc. (product introduction).andO;Ticker:    AAPL.andO;Product:   Apple TokenTalk NB Card (Circuit board)AppleTalk 2.0 (Local area network)AppleTalk Internet Router (Computer network software) (productintroduction).andO;Topic: ; Communications Boards-CardsNetwork Management SoftwareToken Ring NetworksConnectivityRoutingSoftware PackagesProduct Introduction.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Apple's networking day: June 7. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Apple plans networking product blitz for JuneandM;Cupertino, Calif.andP;  -- Apple has set June 7 as the date for a communicationsproduct blitz that will give corporate users links to IBM Token-Ring Networksand a more flexible AppleTalk network.andP;  Developers will be briefed on theannouncements at a worldwide conference of developers next month, sourcessaid.andM;The products, which range from a long-awaited token-ring adapter card for theMac to a new version of AppleTalk that will allow up to 65,025 nodes, arepart of Apple's continuing strategy to sell more Macs in the Fortune 500market, industry sources said.andM;According to sources, the major new products to be introduced include:andM;* A 4-Mbits-per-second (Mbps) token-ring adapter card co-developed with SytekInc. of Mountain View, Calif.andP;  Called TokenTalk, the card will be priced atabout $1,200.andP;  A 16-Mbps card, developed entirely within Apple, is expectedsometime in 1990.andM;Both cards are based on Apple's Macintosh Coprocessor Platform, anintelligent NuBus card with a real-time multitasking operating system,sources said.andP;  Apple's 4-Mbps card will incorporate a high-performance TexasInstruments chip set, a 10-MHz 68000 processor and 512 Kbytes of memory.andM;* AppleTalk 2.0, which will remove AppleTalk's 255-node limit and addbuilt-in links to much faster Ethernet and token-ring networks.andM;According to sources close to Apple, AppleTalk 2.0 adds the concept oflogical zones to AppleTalk, raising the theoretical limit on directconnections to an Ethernet backbone to 65,025.andM;* AppleTalk Internet Router software, which will support links to Ethernetand token-ring networks.andP;  The software can connect up to eight AppleTalkLANs, using the Mac's modem port as well as the printer port previouslyrequired for AppleTalk, according to Apple documents.andM;In addition, Apple is reportedly working on a version of AppleShare calledPersonal AppleShare, geared for smaller networks, that run in the backgroundand use one of the connected Macs as a server.andP;  Sources said the product islikely to be available later in the year.andM;Apple will also use the event to discuss its strategic direction regardingfuture networking architecture, SNA, network management, CL/1, MacAPPC, theCommunications Toolbox and electronic mail.andM;Apple also is reportedly developing a number of other networking products forrelease over the next 18 months (see sidebar at right).andM;&quot;This is encouraging news,&quot; said Dan Mallin of 3M Company of St. Paul, Minn.andO;&quot;Linking different platforms is a top priority for us.&quot;andM;&quot;If 1988 was Apple's year of communications announcements, then 1989 betterbe Apple's year of communications products,&quot; said Peter Lisker, an Oakland,Calif.-based networking consultant.andP;  &quot;The next several months should show usif Apple has its act together.&quot;andO;</TEXT></DOC>